WEBVTT

00:06.406 --> 00:08.508
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good
evening. I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:08.508 --> 00:14.314
On the "NewsHour" tonight: A
potentially catastrophic
hurricane bears down on the
Pacific Coast

00:14.314 --> 00:21.054
of Mexico. Residents and
tourists flee, and the country
declares a state of emergency.

00:21.054 --> 00:25.959
Then: seeking a new way forward
in Syria. Secretary of State
Kerry meets with leaders

00:25.959 --> 00:30.097
from Russia and the Middle East.

00:30.097 --> 00:36.703
Old wind turbines come tumbling
down, part of an effort to save
California's golden eagles.

00:36.703 --> 00:39.439
SHAWN SMALLWOOD, Ecologist:
Those are the most dangerous
turbines in the Altamont Pass

00:39.439 --> 00:43.977
on record. There's one
120-kilowatt turbine down there,
now removed, but it's on record

00:43.977 --> 00:47.514
as having killed one eagle
per year for 10 years.

00:47.514 --> 00:51.885
JUDY WOODRUFF: And it's Friday.
Mark Shields and David Brooks
are here to analyze the week's

00:51.885 --> 00:53.287
news.

00:53.287 --> 00:58.892
All that and more on
tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:58.892 --> 01:03.096
(BREAK)

01:03.096 --> 01:15.175
JUDY WOODRUFF: A storm for the
ages is blasting ashore on
Mexico's West Coast tonight.
Hurricane

01:15.175 --> 01:20.047
Patricia has the strongest
sustained winds ever recorded in
this part of the world, and

01:20.047 --> 01:25.419
it spent in the day in a
slow-motion assault on the
mainland.

01:25.419 --> 01:33.427
Sirens blared and lights flashed
as police and fire units combed
Puerto Vallarta this

01:33.427 --> 01:39.666
morning, urging people to flee
the popular Mexican Pacific
beach resort. The storm burst

01:39.666 --> 01:46.673
to life Tuesday, and, by last
night, it topped the scale, with
winds of 200 miles an hour,

01:46.673 --> 01:50.444
prompting dire descriptions
from Mexico's weather service.

01:50.444 --> 01:53.580
ROBERTO RAMIREZ, Director,
National Water Commission
(through translator): The
National

01:53.580 --> 01:57.117
Hurricane Center in Miami has
determined that this storm is
the strongest storm ever seen

01:57.117 --> 02:00.187
on the American continent.

02:00.187 --> 02:04.057
Additionally, some international
experts have already noted that
this hurricane is the most

02:04.057 --> 02:09.396
powerful hurricane that has ever
existed on the planet in all of
history.

02:09.396 --> 02:15.268
JUDY WOODRUFF: All told, a
hurricane warning stretched
along more than 300 miles of
Mexico's

02:15.268 --> 02:20.507
Pacific Coast. The storm's track
had its center heading between
the bustling port city of

02:20.507 --> 02:25.379
Manzanillo and Puerto
Vallarta tonight.

02:25.379 --> 02:31.385
Heavy rain started falling last
night, and today people hurried
to board up windows,

02:31.385 --> 02:36.790
as crews filled sandbags. The
region's airports closed, and
tourists rushed to check out and

02:36.790 --> 02:38.692
catch flights.

02:38.692 --> 02:43.397
WOMAN: I'm just worried,
because, if we don't get out of
here -- and we drove into town

02:43.397 --> 02:47.968
to get out, which is not the
direction we wanted to go. So,
if we don't make the flight,

02:47.968 --> 02:51.238
then we're -- we are
riding it out here.

02:51.238 --> 02:56.643
JUDY WOODRUFF: Forecasters said
the hurricane will start
weakening tomorrow, as it passes

02:56.643 --> 03:02.315
inland moving north toward
Texas. The remnants will add to
heavy rains already battering

03:02.315 --> 03:06.653
the Lone Star State from
another weather system.

03:06.653 --> 03:11.024
More than 2.5 inches fell at the
Dallas-Fort Worth Airport
yesterday, breaking a record

03:11.024 --> 03:11.992
set in 1908.

03:11.992 --> 03:14.194
MAN: There she goes.

03:14.194 --> 03:19.366
JUDY WOODRUFF: And to the west,
flooding at a mobile home park
picked up trailers and

03:19.366 --> 03:22.302
carried them away.

03:22.302 --> 03:26.973
Today, the mayor of Houston
appealed to people to keep an
eye on what's coming.

03:26.973 --> 03:30.377
ANNISE PARKER (D), Mayor of
Houston, Texas: We really
encourage folks to, once the
rain

03:30.377 --> 03:34.714
starts, just stay home
and stay off the roads.

03:34.714 --> 03:41.721
JUDY WOODRUFF: Patricia is
already being compared with
Typhoon Haiyan that left more
than 7,300

03:41.721 --> 03:48.061
dead or missing in the
Philippines two years ago. And,
today, as waves pounded the
Mexican

03:48.061 --> 03:54.501
coast, one expert warned, "It's
looking like a very bad disaster
is shaping up."

03:54.501 --> 03:59.840
We get an on-the- ground
dispatch from a makeshift storm
shelter in Puerto Vallarta.

03:59.840 --> 04:04.778
David Alire Garcia is there for
Reuters. I spoke with him by
Skype late this afternoon

04:04.778 --> 04:07.581
as the hurricane moved
closer to landfall.

04:07.581 --> 04:10.450
David, thank you for
talking with us.

04:10.450 --> 04:14.821
First of all, tell us where you
are and what are the state of
preparations there?

04:14.821 --> 04:18.391
DAVID ALIRE GARCIA, Reuters:
Well, I'm in Puerto Vallarta.
I'm in the Univa Catholic

04:18.391 --> 04:21.928
university campus, which
is a makeshift shelter.

04:21.928 --> 04:25.966
Wasn't supposed to be a shelter,
but because of problems with
other nearby shelters,
particularly

04:25.966 --> 04:31.271
a big convention center and
risks of flooding, this was
opened up. And now there's about

04:31.271 --> 04:34.875
500 people here, a mix of
tourists, but also many locals
as well.

04:34.875 --> 04:39.579
JUDY WOODRUFF: What about the
state of preparations in that
area, Puerto Vallarta?

04:39.579 --> 04:42.983
DAVID ALIRE GARCIA: Well, the
local government, the state
government, the municipal
government

04:42.983 --> 04:47.854
opened up more than a dozen
shelters. There have been
problems with some, like I just

04:47.854 --> 04:50.457
mentioned a second ago, that
have been opened and then closed
because of worries that they're

04:50.457 --> 04:52.425
too close to rivers.

04:52.425 --> 04:57.531
The authorities are everywhere
here. They're trucking in
people. Just a little while ago,

04:57.531 --> 05:02.569
there were a handful of trucks
that arrived. I think this
shelter is about at its
capacity.

05:02.569 --> 05:06.573
But there are thousands of folks
who need shelter, and it's not
entirely clear that

05:06.573 --> 05:09.109
all of them are
going to get that.

05:09.109 --> 05:13.547
But it seems like the
authorities are -- you know, if
you listen to radio or TV,
there's

05:13.547 --> 05:17.484
all kinds of announcements that
people find shelter and find
someplace safe and get off

05:17.484 --> 05:19.586
the streets.

05:19.586 --> 05:24.658
JUDY WOODRUFF: It still appears,
though, that this storm has
formed very, very quickly,

05:24.658 --> 05:29.963
that it wasn't really until late
last night that people
understood the gravity of it.

05:29.963 --> 05:32.766
Do you think -- is it your sense
that people have evacuated who
needed to evacuate?

05:32.766 --> 05:36.703
DAVID ALIRE GARCIA: I think so.

05:36.703 --> 05:42.609
Just earlier, I was driving
around the tourist part of
Puerto Vallarta, and there are
-- you

05:42.609 --> 05:47.581
know, it's a ghost town. Windows
are boarded up. Windows are
taped up. There's sandbags

05:47.581 --> 05:51.551
at the hotels protecting
storefronts, bars, restaurants.
Of course, it's a big tourist

05:51.551 --> 05:54.054
hub here.

05:54.054 --> 05:58.758
So it seems like there is a lot
of preparation going on. Time
will tell if it really is
adequate

05:58.758 --> 06:01.595
for the storm that's
about to arrive.

06:01.595 --> 06:05.131
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, as I speak
to you, it's just a little after
4:00 Eastern. It looks

06:05.131 --> 06:08.435
like the weather is still
pretty calm right now.

06:08.435 --> 06:12.739
DAVID ALIRE GARCIA: You know,
that's the crazy thing right now
is that there is barely a

06:12.739 --> 06:17.110
tiny drizzle, that there is
hardly any wind, if you can see
behind me. Right, actually,

06:17.110 --> 06:21.881
here, there's a lot of
folks taking refuge here.

06:21.881 --> 06:25.919
And the weather conditions at
the moment are not that bad,
but, of course, you know, things

06:25.919 --> 06:29.990
are projected to get a lot
worse, particularly the winds,
which could have caused a lot of

06:29.990 --> 06:36.062
damage and have caused damage.
There was a big hurricane here
over -- a few years back

06:36.062 --> 06:40.133
that many people still remember
that did cause lots of damage
because of flying debris.

06:40.133 --> 06:44.271
And so I think that's one of the
main worries, in addition to
flooding in the low-lying areas

06:44.271 --> 06:46.673
here in Puerto Vallarta, that
most people are concerned about.

06:46.673 --> 06:51.044
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we hope you
and everyone else is able to
stay safe.

06:51.044 --> 06:52.812
David Alire Garcia,
we thank you.

06:52.812 --> 06:55.815
DAVID ALIRE GARCIA: Thank you.

06:55.815 --> 07:02.322
JUDY WOODRUFF: We will turn to
how this storm got so big so
fast after the news summary.

07:02.322 --> 07:07.627
In other news, Two dozen states,
including West Virginia, Texas,
and Florida, went to

07:07.627 --> 07:13.600
federal court today to block
curbs on carbon dioxide
emissions. The U.S.
Environmental

07:13.600 --> 07:20.240
Protection Agency's Clean Power
Plan seeks to curb the power
plant emissions by 32 percent

07:20.240 --> 07:26.546
in 2030 from 2005 levels. The
states say the move is illegal
overreach and will devastate

07:26.546 --> 07:29.883
their economies.

07:29.883 --> 07:34.788
For the second time this week, a
candidate has dropped out of the
contest for the Democratic

07:34.788 --> 07:41.027
presidential nomination. Lincoln
Chafee, former Rhode Island
senator and governor, and
one-time

07:41.027 --> 07:45.799
Republican, had struggled to
raise money and make any
impression in the polls. Chafee
made

07:45.799 --> 07:49.903
his announcement today during a
speech to a Democratic women's
event in Washington.

07:49.903 --> 07:53.940
LINCOLN CHAFEE (D), Presidential
Candidate: I pledge all my
energy towards a big 2016

07:53.940 --> 07:57.911
victory for Democrats across the
country. But after much thought,
I have decided to

07:57.911 --> 08:02.582
end my campaign for the
president today. Thank you.

08:02.582 --> 08:05.585
JUDY WOODRUFF: Former Virginia
Senator Jim Webb dropped out of
the Democratic race a

08:05.585 --> 08:08.655
couple of days ago.

08:08.655 --> 08:13.760
On the Republican side, there
was word that Jeb Bush is
imposing across-the-board salary

08:13.760 --> 08:19.065
cuts for his staff, and is
downsizing his campaign
headquarters in Miami. News
accounts

08:19.065 --> 08:23.937
cited an internal memo on
this -- money-saving moves.

08:23.937 --> 08:30.543
Suicide bombers killed and
wounded scores of Muslims today
in Nigeria and Pakistan.

08:30.543 --> 08:36.649
At least 42 people died in
Nigeria in attacks on mosques in
two cities. More than a hundred

08:36.649 --> 08:42.589
others were wounded. Far to the
northeast in a city in Southern
Pakistan, a suicide

08:42.589 --> 08:48.061
bomber killed at least 18 people
in a Shiite religious
procession.

08:48.061 --> 08:54.434
The Balkan nations of Serbia and
Croatia have agreed to move more
refugees by train, and

08:54.434 --> 09:00.774
get them out of the rain and
cold. Last night, at least 5,000
people spent the night in
near-freezing

09:00.774 --> 09:05.145
weather near one border
crossing. The Croatian interior
minister called it -- quote --
"torture."

09:05.145 --> 09:07.580
Meanwhile,

09:07.580 --> 09:12.652
Greece reported a record 48,000
people crossed this week from
Turkey. Prime Minister Alexis

09:12.652 --> 09:16.022
Tsipras said it has to stop.

09:16.022 --> 09:21.227
ALEXIS TSIPRAS, Greek Prime
Minister (through translator):
Only if we are able to transfer

09:21.227 --> 09:25.899
the front line from the Greek
islands to the Turkish shores,
and start the process of
resettling

09:25.899 --> 09:31.037
refugees from the Turkish shores
towards Europe, and not from the
Greek islands to other European

09:31.037 --> 09:34.240
nations, can we then hope to
face and diminish these huge
refugee influxes that are
impossible

09:34.240 --> 09:36.476
to cope with today.

09:36.476 --> 09:42.081
JUDY WOODRUFF: The government of
Turkey, in turn, warned that a
new wave of refugees is

09:42.081 --> 09:48.621
coming, as thousands more
Syrians flee a military
offensive backed by Russian
airstrikes.

09:48.621 --> 09:53.193
Police in Sweden now say that a
masked man who attacked a school
with a sword and knife

09:53.193 --> 09:59.933
yesterday was motivated by race.
He killed two people and wounded
two in Trollhattan.

09:59.933 --> 10:05.839
It's a town with a large
immigrant population. All of the
victims were dark-skinned.
Today,

10:05.839 --> 10:09.542
mourners paid their respects at
a makeshift memorial, while the
local police chief reported

10:09.542 --> 10:11.678
on the investigation.

10:11.678 --> 10:16.850
NICLAS HALLGREN, Trollhattan
Police Chief: We have discovered
a letter in his apartment,

10:16.850 --> 10:25.024
and it has some notes in it that
tells us that he has planned the
act and he also -- he

10:25.024 --> 10:31.631
planned it out of a hate crime
perspective. And he's also told
us by that letter that

10:31.631 --> 10:36.236
he is going to -- he considers
that this will be his final act.

10:36.236 --> 10:42.342
JUDY WOODRUFF: The attack came
as it was announced that as many
as 190,000 asylum seekers may

10:42.342 --> 10:46.679
enter Sweden this year alone.
But, today, the government
agreed to restrict the country's

10:46.679 --> 10:50.950
liberal immigration policies.

10:50.950 --> 10:56.189
France has suffered its
deadliest auto accident in more
than 30 years; 43 people were
killed

10:56.189 --> 11:01.027
today in a collision between a
tour bus and a truck. It
happened on a narrow road near

11:01.027 --> 11:05.231
a town that's about 30
miles east of Bordeaux.

11:05.231 --> 11:09.202
Simon Israel of Independent
Television News filed this
report.

11:09.202 --> 11:15.241
SIMON ISRAEL: A group of
pensioners all from the same
village were on their way to
savor

11:15.241 --> 11:19.312
the delights of traditional
French cuisine. Their coach
collided head on with a lorry

11:19.312 --> 11:22.248
carrying wood.

11:22.248 --> 11:29.122
There was, in the words of a
fire chief, a gigantic blaze; 41
on the coach were killed,

11:29.122 --> 11:35.795
but eight survived because the
driver opened the doors barely
seconds before the crash.

11:35.795 --> 11:40.600
French television has broadcast
a reconstruction of one possible
version of events where the

11:40.600 --> 11:46.172
coach came around a blind
corner just before the crash.

11:46.172 --> 11:51.110
Traumatized families gathered in
the town of Puisseguin to wait
for news. Identification

11:51.110 --> 11:54.414
will clearly take some time.

11:54.414 --> 11:58.718
WOMAN (through translator): I'm
hoping, yes, but I don't know
anything. I don't know. I'm

11:58.718 --> 12:01.487
waiting.

12:01.487 --> 12:07.560
SIMON ISRAEL: The French prime
minister was among various
government officials to visit

12:07.560 --> 12:15.168
the scene today to express what
he described as the nation's
emotion for an appalling
catastrophe.

12:15.168 --> 12:18.705
Among the dead is also believed
to be the lorry driver and his
young son, who was by

12:18.705 --> 12:21.207
his side.

12:21.207 --> 12:25.545
JUDY WOODRUFF: A local lawmaker
said the wreck happened on a
dangerous curve. The president

12:25.545 --> 12:29.515
of France promised
an investigation.

12:29.515 --> 12:34.921
Back in this country, an
American soldier killed in a
hostage rescue in Iraq was
praised

12:34.921 --> 12:41.160
today as a hero who sacrificed
himself. Army Master Sergeant
Joshua Wheeler helped to free

12:41.160 --> 12:47.100
some 70 captives being held by
Islamic State forces. Defense
Secretary Ash Carter said

12:47.100 --> 12:51.604
that Wheeler sacrificed himself
by joining a firefight to aid
Kurdish soldiers that he

12:51.604 --> 12:54.941
was advising.

12:54.941 --> 13:00.513
Former IRS official Lois Lerner
will not face criminal charges
for allegedly targeting Tea

13:00.513 --> 13:05.385
Party groups. The Justice
Department ended a two-year
probe today, and said that it
found

13:05.385 --> 13:10.289
no evidence that anyone at the
IRS acted out of political
motives. Lerner once headed the

13:10.289 --> 13:15.194
unit that handles applications
for tax-exempt status.

13:15.194 --> 13:20.199
And on Wall Street today, a
rally in tech stocks helped push
the broader market higher.

13:20.199 --> 13:26.506
The Dow Jones industrial average
gained 157 points to close at
17646. The Nasdaq rose

13:26.506 --> 13:32.779
nearly 112 points. And
the S&P 500 rose 22.

13:32.779 --> 13:37.517
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
what's next for the strongest
hurricane on record in the

13:37.517 --> 13:43.856
Western Hemisphere; world
leaders seek a solution in
Syria; new wind turbines could
be a lifesaver

13:43.856 --> 13:59.005
for golden eagles,
and much more.

13:59.005 --> 14:03.676
Hurricane Patricia has been
described as potentially one of
the most dangerous storms to
ever hit

14:03.676 --> 14:08.314
the Western Hemisphere.
Meteorologists now say that
Patricia is bringing with it
winds

14:08.314 --> 14:13.619
of 190 miles an hour, down
just slightly from earlier.

14:13.619 --> 14:17.423
William Brangham has more on the
storm itself and what is fueling
it. He recorded this interview

14:17.423 --> 14:21.027
a short time ago, as the storm
was approaching Mexico.

14:21.027 --> 14:25.298
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Bob Henson is
a meteorologist for Weather
Underground, a Web-based weather

14:25.298 --> 14:29.102
service that also has a weekday
show on The Weather Channel.
Henson is also author of

14:29.102 --> 14:32.238
five books on weather
and climate change.

14:32.238 --> 14:37.443
So, Bob Henson, it seems like
meteorologists like yourself
have run out of terms to
describe

14:37.443 --> 14:41.581
the intensity of the storm.
Yesterday, it was a Category 1.
We wake up this morning,

14:41.581 --> 14:45.351
it's a Category 5. How did
this storm get so big so fast?

14:45.351 --> 14:48.321
BOB HENSON, Weather Underground:
It's a true outlier.

14:48.321 --> 14:53.092
You know, there's only a very,
very few hurricanes or typhoons
in world history that we know

14:53.092 --> 14:57.964
about that have intensified so
quickly. They have really only
been observing these systems

14:57.964 --> 15:01.300
in depth for the last several
decades, say, so we can't really
say how strong hurricanes

15:01.300 --> 15:04.437
were in 1900 or 1800.

15:04.437 --> 15:09.509
But, certainly in the modern era
of hurricane hunting and
satellites, for a storm to go

15:09.509 --> 15:16.249
to from a tropical storm to a
Cat 5 in, say, 24 hours,, 30
hours, those kinds of numbers

15:16.249 --> 15:19.385
only happen once in a very rare
while. So, this is up in the
ranks of maybe the top three

15:19.385 --> 15:22.455
or four most rapidly
strengthening storms.

15:22.455 --> 15:27.527
And, basically, it's because it
was over extremely warm water
that went to some depth, so the

15:27.527 --> 15:32.431
winds didn't stir up colder
water to weaken it. And upper
winds were very weak, which

15:32.431 --> 15:36.269
allowed it to intensify rapidly.
Really, just all the ingredients
came together in just

15:36.269 --> 15:39.338
the right way, which,
surprisingly, doesn't happen all
that often.

15:39.338 --> 15:44.310
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You mentioned
that calling this a Category 5,
which is the top of the

15:44.310 --> 15:48.981
Saffir-Simpson scale, is almost
an insufficient description of
this storm. Can you explain?

15:48.981 --> 15:51.751
BOB HENSON: Yes.

15:51.751 --> 15:56.255
The Saffir-Simpson scale was
developed several decades ago,
and it breaks hurricanes down

15:56.255 --> 16:01.260
into five bins, Category 1 all
the way up to Category 5. Now,
most of those bins are

16:01.260 --> 16:06.599
about
28-to-30-miles-per-hour-wide,
you might put it. Category 5
starts at 156 miles an

16:06.599 --> 16:10.670
hour, but it has no
ceiling. It's 156 and up.

16:10.670 --> 16:17.543
This storm had peak winds of
200, so it was 45 miles an hour
above the Category 5 threshold.

16:17.543 --> 16:23.649
You might say that, if we had a
Cat 6 and Cat 7, that it would
fall in the Cat 7 range,

16:23.649 --> 16:30.356
close to that. We don't parse
storms out when they get so
strong, in part because once you

16:30.356 --> 16:34.460
get to Cat 5, it pretty much
destroys everything except a
really well-constructed
building,

16:34.460 --> 16:38.231
so there is not as much
operational significance to it.

16:38.231 --> 16:40.833
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, at that
level of intensity, is that what
we're expecting that is going

16:40.833 --> 16:44.570
to just cause some incredible
damage on the coast of Mexico?

16:44.570 --> 16:48.841
BOB HENSON: Well, fortunately,
it has weakened a little bit as
it has approached land. It's

16:48.841 --> 16:52.478
still a very, very powerful
hurricane, still a Category 5,
as in the most recent
observations

16:52.478 --> 16:55.548
within the last couple of hours.

16:55.548 --> 17:00.586
Now, the storm surge is going to
be pretty significant over a
relatively small area.

17:00.586 --> 17:04.390
And that's another blessing with
this storm. It's not a gigantic
hurricane. But there will

17:04.390 --> 17:10.529
be an area of a few miles where
I would expect very, very severe
destruction. And, moreover,

17:10.529 --> 17:15.067
when it runs into very steep
mountains and hillsides just
inland, it is going to be
dumping

17:15.067 --> 17:19.839
gigantic amounts of rain, again,
over not a gigantic area, but
there could be tremendous

17:19.839 --> 17:23.442
amounts of rain along the way.
So, mudslides and floods are
also going to be a real issue.

17:23.442 --> 17:27.647
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And then my
understanding is that the storm
is likely to continue on

17:27.647 --> 17:30.983
breaking up somewhat, but then
heading into Southern Texas.
What are you forecasting for

17:30.983 --> 17:33.552
Texas to be looking at?

17:33.552 --> 17:37.189
BOB HENSON: Still pretty stout
winds. There will be some high
water along the Texas coast,

17:37.189 --> 17:41.460
but mainly a lot of rain. Could
be six to 12 inches of rain in
places like Houston.

17:41.460 --> 17:45.564
And there is an ongoing heavy
rain event over Texas already
because of a separate storm,

17:45.564 --> 17:50.369
so there's going to be some
very, very large local rainfall
amounts. And Texas is notorious

17:50.369 --> 17:55.374
for October systems that bring
in tropical moisture and
ex-hurricanes from the Pacific.

17:55.374 --> 17:56.842
So this is really something
to watch as well.

17:56.842 --> 17:58.311
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: OK.

17:58.311 --> 18:01.347
Bob Henson of Weather
Underground, thank you very
much.

18:01.347 --> 18:10.289
BOB HENSON: Thank you.

18:10.289 --> 18:17.430
JUDY WOODRUFF: Secretary of
State John Kerry met in Vienna
today with his counterparts

18:17.430 --> 18:21.534
from Russia, Turkey and Saudi
Arabia in a renewed quest to
find a political settlement

18:21.534 --> 18:23.602
for the war in Syria.

18:23.602 --> 18:26.205
He spoke to reporters
afterwards.

18:26.205 --> 18:33.612
JOHN KERRY, U.S. Secretary of
State: Today, we came here aware
of all of the pitfalls,

18:33.612 --> 18:38.718
aware of all of the hurdles.
Every foreign minister here has
been wrestling with this

18:38.718 --> 18:46.092
issue for a period of time. But
we came here with a commitment
to try to find new ideas

18:46.092 --> 18:49.695
for how to break the impasse
and end the conflict.

18:49.695 --> 18:55.668
JUDY WOODRUFF: This came after
an agreement Monday between the
U.S. and Russian militaries

18:55.668 --> 19:01.374
on how to avoid accidental
midair collisions as both
countries bomb Syria. And also
that

19:01.374 --> 19:06.445
day, Syrian President Assad met
with President Putin in Moscow.
It was the first time Assad

19:06.445 --> 19:11.250
has left Syria since
the war began in 2011.

19:11.250 --> 19:15.087
For more on the state of play
between the U.S. and Russia over
Syria, we turn to "NewsHour"

19:15.087 --> 19:18.224
chief foreign affairs
correspondent Margaret Warner,
who has been following all of
this.

19:18.224 --> 19:20.726
Margaret, thank you.

19:20.726 --> 19:26.132
So, we know that the U.S.,
Russia and these other countries
have been trying for two years,

19:26.132 --> 19:31.771
at least, to talk about, to find
a political settlement. No
results. Today any different?

19:31.771 --> 19:34.807
MARGARET WARNER: It's
very hard to tell, Judy.

19:34.807 --> 19:37.610
The one thing that indicates
there maybe progress is that
they agreed they are going to
meet

19:37.610 --> 19:44.517
again next week, at the end of
next week. Well, when Secretary
Kerry said, well, people

19:44.517 --> 19:48.554
brought a lot of new ideas,
publicly, we heard no new ideas.
What we heard was the same
mantra:

19:48.554 --> 19:51.090
We all agree it should be a
united Syria, it should be
democratic, and secular, and

19:51.090 --> 19:54.226
be diverse.

19:54.226 --> 19:59.665
But there was no resolution of
this huge hump over Assad's
future. And, you know, Turkey

19:59.665 --> 20:04.637
and Saudi want him gone now.
Russia wants -- afraid of the
chaos that could result if

20:04.637 --> 20:08.908
he were to fall precipitously
and wants him to stay. The U.S.
is the only one that has

20:08.908 --> 20:12.344
shown nay leg on that. It was
pretty clear from what Kerry
said today that the U.S. is

20:12.344 --> 20:17.349
willing to consider a transition
in which Assad may remain for a
while.

20:17.349 --> 20:22.221
JUDY WOODRUFF: Margaret, what
effect is Russia's military
intervention in Syria, which the

20:22.221 --> 20:24.990
U.S. has not been happy with,
what effect is that having on
those talks?

20:24.990 --> 20:27.359
MARGARET WARNER: Well,
it's interesting.

20:27.359 --> 20:31.330
Secretary Kerry has been telling
aides that actually this could
be an opportunity, that

20:31.330 --> 20:34.533
it could be an action-forcing
event, even though, as you said,
the U.S. was furious

20:34.533 --> 20:38.504
about this, because
it strengthens Assad.

20:38.504 --> 20:43.876
But the fact is, it has given
Russia a different seat at the
table in terms of figuring out

20:43.876 --> 20:50.282
Syria's future. One, it means
Russia has now a real interest
in getting this resolved
politically,

20:50.282 --> 20:52.284
or it's going to be sitting
there -- it's going to be
bombing forever. It's going to

20:52.284 --> 20:55.821
be in a kind of
military quagmire.

20:55.821 --> 21:01.594
So, it's also forced the United
States, you have noticed, to up
its game in Syria, more

21:01.594 --> 21:06.765
weapons to the rebels. It
revived the discussion
internally about whether to
establish a no-fly

21:06.765 --> 21:12.104
zone. So, there is a feeling
that, to a great extent, of
course, the U.S. doesn't trust

21:12.104 --> 21:17.610
what Putin's up to, but that
something may happen as a
result.

21:17.610 --> 21:21.413
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, what about
the meeting that happened this
week in Moscow where Assad

21:21.413 --> 21:25.050
flew to Moscow to meet with
Putin? What's known about that?

21:25.050 --> 21:28.854
MARGARET WARNER: What is known
about that, at least from
Russian sources I have -- and

21:28.854 --> 21:32.958
it was secondhand -- is that,
one, it was very chilly. As one
said to me, no one likes

21:32.958 --> 21:35.561
Assad.

21:35.561 --> 21:41.567
Two, that Putin was very firm
about, one, they wanted to
coordinate Russian airpower

21:41.567 --> 21:45.571
with Syrian ground troops. He
made it clear that Russia wasn't
going to send in ground

21:45.571 --> 21:47.973
troops, but he also wanted to
make sure the targeting was good
so they didn't kill a mass

21:47.973 --> 21:51.844
of civilians, that
the Russians didn't.

21:51.844 --> 21:55.681
But then they did discuss the
transition, but I'm told that
though they talked about

21:55.681 --> 22:00.753
the need for a diverse one, and
Assad, of course, of course,
that in fact Putin didn't

22:00.753 --> 22:03.289
pull the trigger and say, and,
you know, Mr. President Assad,
that will mean you have to

22:03.289 --> 22:05.024
go.

22:05.024 --> 22:08.460
So one person said to me, I have
a feeling they were talking past
each other.

22:08.460 --> 22:14.133
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Margaret, if
Putin wants some kind of
improved relationship with the

22:14.133 --> 22:18.003
U.S., wants to work something
out, what are the prospects for
that happening?

22:18.003 --> 22:22.608
MARGARET WARNER: Well, the
administration believes they're
not great, but that if -- there

22:22.608 --> 22:27.413
are two things he could do, one,
change the targeting from 85 to
90 percent moderate rebels,

22:27.413 --> 22:32.651
which is who he is hitting now,
instead of ISIS, and, two,
really use his enhanced leverage

22:32.651 --> 22:37.723
now with Assad, because he's got
Assad's back, to really push
Assad to recognize that,
ultimately,

22:37.723 --> 22:41.327
he has to agree to a
process in which he goes.

22:41.327 --> 22:45.631
And why would we do that? One,
because he's so eager to end his
international isolation

22:45.631 --> 22:50.469
and the sanctions. And, two, as
I referred to earlier, he now
has reason to fear of being

22:50.469 --> 22:53.772
sucked into kind of military
quicksand in Syria, if it just
goes on and on and on and

22:53.772 --> 22:56.208
there's no political solution.

22:56.208 --> 23:03.649
JUDY WOODRUFF: Margaret Warner,
some great reporting. We thank
you.

23:03.649 --> 23:09.722
MARGARET WARNER: Thanks, Judy.

23:09.722 --> 23:14.893
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

23:14.893 --> 23:20.499
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
Benghazi, presidential politics,
and Paul Ryan, we discuss it all

23:20.499 --> 23:25.271
with Mark Shields and David
Brooks; and who's in charge of
American schools? -- journalist

23:25.271 --> 23:29.275
Dale Russakoff investigates
in her new book.

23:29.275 --> 23:34.947
But, first, we turn to the topic
of wind power. It's the
country's fastest growing energy

23:34.947 --> 23:39.618
source, expected
to triple by 2040.

23:39.618 --> 23:45.691
But the giant wind turbines can
also pose a threat to wildlife.
Thousands of birds are

23:45.691 --> 23:51.730
killed each year when they run
into turbines or are hit by
their blades. Now scientists

23:51.730 --> 23:55.534
at one of the nation's oldest
wind farms have developed a
strategy to help save protected

23:55.534 --> 23:58.470
species.

23:58.470 --> 24:04.043
Our colleagues at public TV
station KQED in San Francisco
bring you this story produced

24:04.043 --> 24:08.947
by Gabriela Quiros and
narrated by Scott Shafer.

24:08.947 --> 24:15.020
SCOTT SHAFER: The Altamont Pass,
east of San Francisco, is home
to hundreds of bird species.

24:15.020 --> 24:19.124
They hunt and play in the midst
of 3,000 wind turbines, which
can be deadly, especially

24:19.124 --> 24:20.592
to golden eagles.

24:20.592 --> 24:21.894
MAN: There's an
eagle right there.

24:21.894 --> 24:22.661
MAN: Eagle, eagle,
eagle, eagle, eagle.

24:22.661 --> 24:23.762
MAN: Right here flying below...

24:23.762 --> 24:26.231
MAN: OK, below the horizon.

24:26.231 --> 24:31.036
SCOTT SHAFER: Biologists Doug
Bell, Shawn Smallwood and Joe
DiDonato study golden eagles.

24:31.036 --> 24:34.540
MAN: We have got some good wind
going today, so this might be a
good day for seeing a few

24:34.540 --> 24:36.442
eagles.

24:36.442 --> 24:40.546
DOUG BELL, East Bay Regional
Park District: The Altamont Pass
Wind Resource Area is within

24:40.546 --> 24:44.917
and adjacent to one of the
densest nesting populations of
golden eagles in the world.

24:44.917 --> 24:50.255
SCOTT SHAFER: Golden eagles are
protected under federal law.
According to county estimates,

24:50.255 --> 24:54.960
35 golden eagles were killed by
the Altamont's turbines in 2013.

24:54.960 --> 25:00.766
DOUG BELL: Their population is
going down the drain. The
Altamont is killing more eagles

25:00.766 --> 25:03.769
than the local population
can reproduce.

25:03.769 --> 25:06.038
KRYSTA ROGERS, California
Department of Fish and Wildlife:
The primary injury on this bird

25:06.038 --> 25:09.942
is the left wing. The
carpal bone is shattered.

25:09.942 --> 25:14.980
SCOTT SHAFER: Today, Krysta
Rogers of the California
Department of Fish and Wildlife

25:14.980 --> 25:19.351
Examines a golden eagle that was
found injured on an Altamont
Pass wind farm. The bird had

25:19.351 --> 25:21.286
to be euthanized.

25:21.286 --> 25:27.326
KRYSTA ROGERS: We describe this
as blunt-force trauma, which is
consistent with a wind turbine

25:27.326 --> 25:30.362
strike, given the location
where the bird was found.

25:30.362 --> 25:34.867
MAN: The transmitter is going to
stay on here about three years.

25:34.867 --> 25:41.273
SCOTT SHAFER: The dead golden
eagle was one of 18 that
researchers had been tracking.

25:41.273 --> 25:44.376
Though four of them have died
after hitting turbines,
scientists were still able to
recover

25:44.376 --> 25:46.912
valuable data.

25:46.912 --> 25:50.115
DOUG BELL: One of the more
valuable things that we have
learned from our transmitters

25:50.115 --> 25:54.420
that we placed on eagles is that
they use the Altamont a lot.
They go in and out throughout

25:54.420 --> 25:58.390
the course of the year. They
will spend weeks at a time
there.

25:58.390 --> 26:03.295
SCOTT SHAFER: For more than a
decade, environmental groups
have been trying to get wind
companies

26:03.295 --> 26:07.833
to protect birds in this area,
says the Audubon Society's
Michael Lynes.

26:07.833 --> 26:11.203
MICHAEL LYNES, Audubon Society:
The Altamont was sort of seen as
a black eye for renewable

26:11.203 --> 26:13.839
energy, because any time someone
was proposing a new wind farm,
it would raise the specter

26:13.839 --> 26:16.141
of the Altamont Pass.

26:16.141 --> 26:20.546
SCOTT SHAFER: After chapters of
the Audubon Society and other
environmental groups sued

26:20.546 --> 26:25.484
to get birds protected, wind
companies agreed to take down
old wind turbines.

26:25.484 --> 26:29.688
MICHAEL LYNES: We wanted to move
towards getting the old turbines
out of the Altamont Pass

26:29.688 --> 26:34.593
because, in a process called
repowering, up to 30 old
turbines can be replaced with
one

26:34.593 --> 26:39.665
single new turbine, which then
results usually in significantly
less bird mortality.

26:39.665 --> 26:46.071
SCOTT SHAFER: At this wind farm,
300 turbines are coming down and
being replaced by only

26:46.071 --> 26:49.975
10 new ones, which together will
produce double the amount of
electricity, enough to power

26:49.975 --> 26:53.312
12,000 homes for a year.

26:53.312 --> 26:55.981
RICK MILLER, EDF Renewable
Energy: It's time to pull the
old machines down and put new

26:55.981 --> 26:58.217
ones up.

26:58.217 --> 27:04.256
SCOTT SHAFER: Rick Miller of EDF
Renewable Energy, which owns the
wind farm, says the

27:04.256 --> 27:08.160
repowering process will cost $35
million and is facilitated by
federal tax credits for

27:08.160 --> 27:10.128
wind energy.

27:10.128 --> 27:14.867
RICK MILLER: The turbines are
becoming much larger, much
larger rotor diameters and much

27:14.867 --> 27:18.337
taller towers. So we have really
been able to reduce the number
of turbines required

27:18.337 --> 27:22.374
to produce a tremendous amount
of energy from the same site.

27:22.374 --> 27:27.079
SCOTT SHAFER: And that means
there are fewer turbines for
birds to hit. Companies can also

27:27.079 --> 27:29.348
place the turbines
more strategically.

27:29.348 --> 27:32.117
SHAWN SMALLWOOD, Ecologist:
Three hundred meters above
ground.

27:32.117 --> 27:34.987
SCOTT SHAFER: Ecologist Shawn
Smallwood advises companies on
where to put their turbines to

27:34.987 --> 27:37.656
minimize bird deaths.

27:37.656 --> 27:40.559
SHAWN SMALLWOOD: This is where
the old turbines were, and this
is also where the burrowing

27:40.559 --> 27:44.096
owls nest. And so the fatality
rate was pretty high.

27:44.096 --> 27:48.767
SCOTT SHAFER: This wind farm was
one of the first to get new,
more efficient turbines.

27:48.767 --> 27:52.137
SHAWN SMALLWOOD: When we
repower, we put the new turbines
up on the top of the hill, where

27:52.137 --> 27:55.841
the burrowing owls are not. So,
our burrowing owl fatality rate
dropped to zero in three

27:55.841 --> 27:58.377
years of monitoring,
and that's why.

27:58.377 --> 28:03.415
SCOTT SHAFER: Smallwood says
that when wind energy companies
first installed over 7,000

28:03.415 --> 28:09.121
turbines in the Altamont Pass in
the 1980s, they gave little
consideration to bird safety.

28:09.121 --> 28:15.260
SHAWN SMALLWOOD: Those are the
most dangerous turbines in the
Altamont Pass on record. There's

28:15.260 --> 28:19.231
one 120-kilowatt turbine down
there, now removed, but it's on
record as having killed one
eagle

28:19.231 --> 28:21.867
per year for 10 years. And the
reason is because there's a lot
of eagle traffic through the

28:21.867 --> 28:23.969
lowest spots of the
Altamont Pass.

28:23.969 --> 28:30.809
SCOTT SHAFER: Birds fly lower in
some areas to avoid wind
resistance and to hunt for prey.

28:30.809 --> 28:35.147
But, with their keen eyesight
focused on the ground, eagles
might not see a wind turbine

28:35.147 --> 28:38.183
blade until it's too late.

28:38.183 --> 28:43.655
SHAWN SMALLWOOD: Social
interactions are very important.
So, an eagle responding to other

28:43.655 --> 28:47.693
eagles, chase each other around
or chase some other birds, these
are dangerous social
interactions

28:47.693 --> 28:51.396
that lead up to what we
call events, near-misses.

28:51.396 --> 28:56.435
SCOTT SHAFER: The federal
government is increasing
enforcement of laws aimed at
protecting golden

28:56.435 --> 28:59.938
eagles, including bringing
criminal charges against two
companies whose turbines killed

28:59.938 --> 29:03.375
golden eagles in Wyoming.

29:03.375 --> 29:08.480
Scott Flaherty of the U.S. Fish
and Wildlife Service says that
was a significant step.

29:08.480 --> 29:11.383
SCOTT FLAHERTY, U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service: The
prosecution of those two
companies certainly

29:11.383 --> 29:14.152
sent a message to companies
across the country there is
incentive there to come in and
work

29:14.152 --> 29:16.455
with us.

29:16.455 --> 29:21.159
SCOTT SHAFER: That incentive is
a new permitting system that
allows companies to kill a
limited

29:21.159 --> 29:26.031
number of eagles each year. Even
the Audubon Society's Michael
Lynes sees permits as a

29:26.031 --> 29:28.367
positive step.

29:28.367 --> 29:32.938
MICHAEL LYNES: Before, it was
sort of chaos. There was no real
regulation. There was no

29:32.938 --> 29:36.942
real enforcement. And we know
birds were getting killed in
large numbers. Now we can
actually

29:36.942 --> 29:41.480
keep track of that. We can hold
people accountable, and we can
take steps to remedy the
problem.

29:41.480 --> 29:47.052
SCOTT SHAFER: As the U.S.
increases its wind power
capability, scientists,
including Shawn

29:47.052 --> 29:52.357
Smallwood, believe fewer
turbines and better placement
are key to protecting wildlife.

29:52.357 --> 29:57.496
SHAWN SMALLWOOD: We have learned
a lot here. And so it should be
the number one laboratory

29:57.496 --> 30:01.600
in the country for learning what
not to do wrong with wind
development around the rest

30:01.600 --> 30:03.168
of the country.

30:03.168 --> 30:08.707
SCOTT SHAFER: For the "PBS
NewsHour," I'm Scott Shafer.

30:08.707 --> 30:21.119
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's been a busy
week in the political world.

30:21.119 --> 30:27.292
