33:17.062 --> 33:22.033
the previous hearing, to show
exasperation, to display temper.

33:22.033 --> 33:27.138
And she just -- she came off it,
to use an adjective,
presidential. And I just think

33:27.138 --> 33:33.812
-- I just think that the
Republicans ought to drop this
and move on, but I think it is

33:33.812 --> 33:39.551
-- I think it is symptomatic of
a party that is incapable of
accepting its governing
responsibility.

33:39.551 --> 33:41.019
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just quickly,
David, Republicans, how -- are
they hurt by this or do they
just

33:41.019 --> 33:43.455
move on?

33:43.455 --> 33:46.758
DAVID BROOKS: Not really. I
don't think they're really hurt.
I don't take the broad
indictment.

33:46.758 --> 33:52.564
Sometimes, a scandal cottage
industry gets started, and it's
fed by people who get expertise,

33:52.564 --> 33:57.135
and then the talk radio get into
it, and they get into the weeds.
And they imagine something

33:57.135 --> 34:02.207
that big is about to happen, and
the scandal cottage industries
just go on forever.

34:02.207 --> 34:06.945
And they think they hurt Hillary
Clinton's poll numbers this way,
but I swear, if they

34:06.945 --> 34:12.317
want to take a real issue, the
disarray of our Middle East
policy is a real issue.
Benghazi,

34:12.317 --> 34:17.255
if you list our foreign policy
issues of importance, it would
be number 197.

34:17.255 --> 34:21.726
JUDY WOODRUFF: I think you have
to say, Mark, this was a pretty
good week for former Secretary

34:21.726 --> 34:26.698
of State Clinton, not only the
general interpretation of the
hearings, the fact that she
doesn't

34:26.698 --> 34:30.502
have an opponent that many
people thought she could have in
Vice President Joe Biden.

34:30.502 --> 34:33.571
He said he's not running.

34:33.571 --> 34:37.776
Where does that leave
everything? What did you make of
his decision? Were you
surprised?

34:37.776 --> 34:41.646
MARK SHIELDS: Well, I was
surprised, because I didn't
know.

34:41.646 --> 34:47.319
Everybody who said they knew who
was talking didn't know, and
everybody who apparently

34:47.319 --> 34:54.192
knew wasn't talking. But I
didn't know that he wasn't going
to run.

34:54.192 --> 35:00.332
I will say this about Joe Biden.
His absence means that the happy
warrior will be missing

35:00.332 --> 35:07.405
from the Democratic battle this
year. That's what Joe -- Joe
Biden has personally at least

35:07.405 --> 35:10.241
35 percent of the world's known
reserve of authenticity.

35:10.241 --> 35:11.509
(LAUGHTER)

35:11.509 --> 35:14.813
MARK SHIELDS: And we're
looking for the authentic.

35:14.813 --> 35:20.952
Lindsey Graham, Republican from
South Carolina, who is himself a
presidential candidate and

35:20.952 --> 35:27.092
an active partisan, said of Joe
Biden, if you don't like Joe
Biden, you ought take a

35:27.092 --> 35:29.828
serious look at yourself,
because there is something wrong
with you.

35:29.828 --> 35:34.933
He is the nicest person I have
ever met. God never made a
better man than Joe Biden. This

35:34.933 --> 35:39.371
was before Joe Biden pulled out.
This was just in an interview in
Iowa a couple -- a

35:39.371 --> 35:45.243
month or so ago. So I just think
it takes a lot of courage to
run. It takes a lot more

35:45.243 --> 35:52.017
courage to pull out. And I just
-- I will miss him and his
presence in this race.

35:52.017 --> 35:54.886
JUDY WOODRUFF: The fact that
he's not in, what effect does it
have?

35:54.886 --> 35:58.456
DAVID BROOKS: Yes. Well,
obviously, it makes Hillary even
more -- she's gone from the
doldrums

35:58.456 --> 36:02.127
of three months ago now to the
unstoppable behemoth that no one
can touch in the course

36:02.127 --> 36:02.927
of a week.

36:02.927 --> 36:04.562
MARK SHIELDS: That's right.

36:04.562 --> 36:09.200
DAVID BROOKS: It does take away
some of the joy. Biden could be
very eloquent, very much

36:09.200 --> 36:13.505
in touch with working-class
voters. He comes from that
background.

36:13.505 --> 36:15.140
And the other thing about what
he did, the guy was elected
senator, I think, when he

36:15.140 --> 36:15.907
was 29.

36:15.907 --> 36:18.610
MARK SHIELDS:
Twenty-nine. He was.

36:18.610 --> 36:22.047
DAVID BROOKS: And he's now
looking at the end of his
political career. And he's a
political

36:22.047 --> 36:27.118
creature. He loves politics. He
loves talking to people. And so
even getting out of the

36:27.118 --> 36:31.423
race means that his political
career will end with the
administration, one presumes.

36:31.423 --> 36:34.025
And that's a hard thing for a
guy to say, because he's been
serving all his life and

36:34.025 --> 36:36.294
he's loved the act of service.

36:36.294 --> 36:39.697
JUDY WOODRUFF: Somebody who is
taking -- or trying to take a
step up in his political

36:39.697 --> 36:44.536
career, Mark, is Paul Ryan, who
decided this week that he is
going to run for speaker of

36:44.536 --> 36:48.840
the House. He managed to get
enough of not just Republicans,
but very conservative
Republicans,

36:48.840 --> 36:51.409
to say they're going
to support him.

36:51.409 --> 36:55.313
How did he do that? To do what
John Boehner and Kevin McCarthy
couldn't do, how did this

36:55.313 --> 36:56.848
happen?

36:56.848 --> 37:00.585
MARK SHIELDS: Well, I think
there were a convergence of
things.

37:00.585 --> 37:06.858
Paul Ryan is a near unique
figure in the Republican House,
in the Republican Party. He's
been

37:06.858 --> 37:12.464
a leader on philosophical and
ideological issues. He was the
candidate for vice president.

37:12.464 --> 37:18.870
He's been a leader within the
caucus and respected across all
the divisions.

37:18.870 --> 37:25.410
He laid down conditions, that he
would only accept speakership
and seek it under certain

37:25.410 --> 37:29.881
conditions. Interesting, one was
family and parental leave,
something Republicans have

37:29.881 --> 37:32.417
consistently opposed.
But Paul Ryan...

37:32.417 --> 37:34.619
JUDY WOODRUFF: For himself.

37:34.619 --> 37:37.155
MARK SHIELDS: Paul Ryan wants it
for himself. He wants to spend
-- admirably, he wants to

37:37.155 --> 37:41.826
spend time with his children,
who are in their formative and
teen years.

37:41.826 --> 37:46.131
Would that he would extend this
to all parents. And I'm sure he
will now that he's speaker,

37:46.131 --> 37:46.798
about to be speaker.

37:46.798 --> 37:48.266
(LAUGHTER)

37:48.266 --> 37:53.571
MARK SHIELDS: But I think, Judy,
it was an acknowledgment on the
part of Republicans

37:53.571 --> 37:57.308
of just how desperate their
straits were, that they couldn't
continue to flounder around

37:57.308 --> 38:00.078
as they have.

38:00.078 --> 38:04.349
This is a party, right now,
according to the Wall Street
Journal/NBC and other polls,
that

38:04.349 --> 38:10.855
the party members have no
respect for the party leaders.
And they think -- Republicans

38:10.855 --> 38:16.995
think their own party is in
terrible shape, and whereas
Democrats, either rightly or
wrongly,

38:16.995 --> 38:20.465
think that the Democratic Party
is doing fine or doing OK.

38:20.465 --> 38:25.336
But -- so I just think that this
was an acknowledgement that they
had to turn and swallow some of

38:25.336 --> 38:27.438
their differences.

38:27.438 --> 38:32.877
JUDY WOODRUFF: How does -- what
is it about him, David, that
wasn't acceptable, I mean,

38:32.877 --> 38:36.781
that wasn't there in Boehner and
McCarthy? What does he bring?

38:36.781 --> 38:39.517
DAVID BROOKS: Well, partly, the
Freedom Caucus changed. They are
good at destroying. They're

38:39.517 --> 38:41.419
not good at constructing. And
they knew they needed a leader.
There had to be some party

38:41.419 --> 38:44.589
leader to end what was going on.

38:44.589 --> 38:49.761
And so when Ryan went in to meet
with them, he said, well, if you
want me, fine. I'm out

38:49.761 --> 38:53.831
of here. I don't need this. But
then he looked at their ideas
about changing the way Congress

38:53.831 --> 38:56.234
works, and he didn't concede to
any of them, but he said, well,
those sound like decent

38:56.234 --> 38:58.703
ideas. We will discuss it.

38:58.703 --> 39:03.908
So he showed a little respect.
And they softened. And, mostly,
they softened, and because they

39:03.908 --> 39:08.713
had no real alternative. And so
it was their softening, his
display of respect, and the

39:08.713 --> 39:14.752
fact that he is a -- he is the
most policy-oriented speaker
probably of our lifetimes.

39:14.752 --> 39:18.990
There have been a lot of
politicians who have been
speaker, but he is a policy
person primarily.

39:18.990 --> 39:20.258
And he has worked with
Democrats, with Patty Murray.

39:20.258 --> 39:21.926
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

39:21.926 --> 39:23.828
DAVID BROOKS: He's done some
really tough stuff that he had
to persuade his own party

39:23.828 --> 39:28.066
to endorse, some
entitlement reforms.

39:28.066 --> 39:34.138
And so I think he may actually
help the Republican image,
because, A, he's just an
attractive

39:34.138 --> 39:39.143
guy. He's a nice guy. He's an
outgoing, friendly guy. But, B,
he actually does care about
policies.

39:39.143 --> 39:42.146
And he will be a little more
aggressive in promoting
policies.

39:42.146 --> 39:46.584
And the Tea Party was right
about Boehner. He wasn't
aggressive in promoting ideas.
And

39:46.584 --> 39:50.455
so Democrats were coming out
with proposals and ideas, and
Republicans had a black hole.

39:50.455 --> 39:53.057
JUDY WOODRUFF: But does this
mean, though, that they're going
to -- because he's in place,

39:53.057 --> 39:56.160
that they are now going to be
able to reach agreement on the
debt ceiling and do something

39:56.160 --> 39:58.763
about the highway bill? Does
this mean things are going to
get done now that weren't --
they

39:58.763 --> 40:00.665
couldn't get done before?

40:00.665 --> 40:03.735
DAVID BROOKS: I find it hard to
believe that they would ruin his
early phase by going -- shutting

40:03.735 --> 40:06.404
down the government and not
doing the debt ceiling.

40:06.404 --> 40:10.241
Further down the road,
obviously, he will have the same
problems that Boehner had.

40:10.241 --> 40:18.316
MARK SHIELDS: The party -- the
job description speaker in the
past has not consisted of
including

40:18.316 --> 40:22.654
policy, other than Newt
Gingrich, who was really the
exception there.

40:22.654 --> 40:28.626
I think, Judy, he's making -- in
part of a concession, he's
making a mistake. And I think

40:28.626 --> 40:35.366
that the speaker's job
description has been the one
person who can hold that caucus
together.

40:35.366 --> 40:41.606
And one of the tools used to do
it -- and John Boehner did it
tirelessly, and so did

40:41.606 --> 40:44.876
Nancy Pelosi -- and that is to
go out and speak to members in
their own districts, to

40:44.876 --> 40:48.112
raise money for them.

40:48.112 --> 40:51.783
And Paul Ryan, as I mentioned
earlier, doesn't want to do
that. I don't think you can
subcontract

40:51.783 --> 40:56.087
that out. I really don't. I
think -- and you can't say, gee,
I can't make it this week.

40:56.087 --> 40:57.689
Can Sam or Sally do it?

40:57.689 --> 40:59.557
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why
is that important?

40:59.557 --> 41:04.262
MARK SHIELDS: Because it's the
speaker. And it's a
transactional, personal
relationship

41:04.262 --> 41:09.600
the speaker has with his
members: And I -- remember,
David, I came in when you had
that tough primary

41:09.600 --> 41:12.637
and I said -- and I
need you on this one.

41:12.637 --> 41:17.909
And that's part of being
speaker. I think it's an added
feature that Paul Ryan brings

41:17.909 --> 41:23.748
to it, this policy dimension.
But there is no guarantee that
the Freedom Caucus is not

41:23.748 --> 41:27.585
going to bring a motion to
vacate, which is, of course,
what drove John Boehner
ultimately,

41:27.585 --> 41:30.722
which is a vote
of no confidence.

41:30.722 --> 41:36.294
And I just -- I think David's
right. John Boehner will try to
clear the decks of as

41:36.294 --> 41:40.965
many as he can of these
controversial items before he
leaves. But December 11 is the
big

41:40.965 --> 41:44.969
day. That's when the government
has to be funded. And it's going
to mean probably taking

41:44.969 --> 41:49.006
the caps off of discretionary
spending and defense spending.
And I think that's where

41:49.006 --> 41:51.609
you're going to see the Freedom
Caucus really rise up.

41:51.609 --> 41:54.712
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right, very
quick, less than a minute,
David.

41:54.712 --> 41:59.150
New poll numbers out in Iowa
that show a surge, at least over
the last two months, for Ben

41:59.150 --> 42:02.787
Carson. He's up 10 points over
what he was in August. Trump is
down a little bit. Cruz

42:02.787 --> 42:05.790
is up. What's going on?

42:05.790 --> 42:09.594
DAVID BROOKS: Two things. The
evangelicals are coalescing
around Carson, and, two, there

42:09.594 --> 42:14.799
are a lot of women who will not
vote for Trump. And so he's
doing poorly among women.

42:14.799 --> 42:18.069
And so I think that is what is
happening there. I still am of
the belief that neither of them

42:18.069 --> 42:19.437
is going to get the nomination.
And so I look to...

42:19.437 --> 42:20.138
(CROSSTALK)

42:20.138 --> 42:21.939
JUDY WOODRUFF: Neither
Trump nor Carson?

42:21.939 --> 42:23.875
DAVID BROOKS: And I look to --
just because that's not the way
history has worked so far.

42:23.875 --> 42:26.611
History sometimes changes.

42:26.611 --> 42:30.081
But Rubio did well in that poll,
so I'm looking at him as the
alternative, if we ever get

42:30.081 --> 42:31.883
normal.

42:31.883 --> 42:34.619
JUDY WOODRUFF: And then Jeb
Bush, Mark, announced today he's
cutting back on staff, cutting

42:34.619 --> 42:36.754
back on his big --
his headquarters.

42:36.754 --> 42:40.091
MARK SHIELDS: Never known a
winning candidate to cut back on
staff spending or to close

42:40.091 --> 42:44.695
offices. So, it isn't good.

42:44.695 --> 42:52.036
I agree with David about Ben
Carson. And he is broadly
acceptable to more people in the

42:52.036 --> 42:57.008
Republican Party. Peter Hart did
a focus group this week of 12
Republican voters in Indiana,

42:57.008 --> 43:01.679
and it came through, their
admiration, affection for him,
his moral leadership, and
they're

43:01.679 --> 43:05.917
-- the doubts and
skepticism about Trump.

43:05.917 --> 43:11.789
And I think this is a problem
that the Republicans have to
deal with. Experience and
holding

43:11.789 --> 43:15.760
an office in this year has
become a liability among
Republicans office seekers.

43:15.760 --> 43:18.029
JUDY WOODRUFF: OK. Fascinating.

43:18.029 --> 43:22.767
Mark Shields, David Brooks,
we thank you, as always.

