43:50.928 --> 43:55.967
It was meant to be a
game-changer for public
education in Newark, New Jersey,
a plan launched

43:55.967 --> 44:02.507
five years ago that might show
the entire country how to remake
failing urban schools.

44:02.507 --> 44:06.978
Reporter Dale Russakoff
chronicled what became of those
efforts in her new book, "The
Prize:

44:06.978 --> 44:10.014
Who's in Charge of
America's Schools?"

44:10.014 --> 44:13.851
William Brangham recently spoke
with her for our "NewsHour"
Bookshelf.

44:13.851 --> 44:18.789
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It started
with an unlikely trio, Newark's
Democratic Mayor Cory Booker,

44:18.789 --> 44:23.494
the state's Republican Governor
Chris Christie, and Facebook
billionaire Mark Zuckerberg,

44:23.494 --> 44:28.766
who offered a whopping $100
million grant. They made the
announcement on "Oprah."

44:28.766 --> 44:33.070
The money was to be used to help
implement many oft school reform
efforts being tried

44:33.070 --> 44:38.042
out nationwide, boost pay for
the best teachers, open more
charter schools and close the
failing

44:38.042 --> 44:42.947
ones. And there have been
successes. Last year, 20 percent
of Newark's black students

44:42.947 --> 44:48.286
were enrolled in -- quote --
"above-average schools." That's
up from 12 percent in 2010,

44:48.286 --> 44:52.123
but those gains came at a price.
The community remains
distrustful of the reforms and
the

44:52.123 --> 44:56.327
exodus to charter schools
has fueled a budget crisis.

44:56.327 --> 45:01.098
In her new book, "The Prize:
Who's in Charge of America's
Schools?" former Washington Post

45:01.098 --> 45:06.337
reporter Dale Russakoff details
where reformers got it right and
where things went wrong.

45:06.337 --> 45:09.407
I talked with her recently about
how Newark's schools and
students are doing five years

45:09.407 --> 45:10.441
on.

45:10.441 --> 45:12.910
Dale Russakoff, thanks
for joining us.

45:12.910 --> 45:11.943
DALE RUSSAKOFF, Author, "The
Prize: Who's in Charge of
America's Schools?": Thanks for

45:11.943 --> 45:14.045
having me.

45:14.045 --> 45:18.282
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: In your book,
you write that the trio behind
this initial effort,

45:18.282 --> 45:23.120
Cory Booker, Chris Christie, and
Mark Zuckerberg, you write about
them this way -- quote -- "Their

45:23.120 --> 45:27.491
stated goal was not to repair
education in Newark, but to
develop a model for saving

45:27.491 --> 45:31.896
it in all of urban America
and to do it in five years."

45:31.896 --> 45:36.667
That is a breathtakingly
ambitious goal. What was their
plan?

45:36.667 --> 45:40.371
DALE RUSSAKOFF: Well, actually,
I think they wanted, first of
all, to repair education

45:40.371 --> 45:45.109
in Newark first, but they saw
that they could create some kind
of a model that could then

45:45.109 --> 45:48.779
be scaled up almost like a
start-up business, which is the
way Zuckerberg would be
comfortable

45:48.779 --> 45:51.782
thinking about it at that time.

45:51.782 --> 45:57.822
But what they thought they would
do was bring in charter schools
and dramatically expand

45:57.822 --> 46:03.260
the existing footprint of the
charter schools, and then also
turn the school district into

46:03.260 --> 46:07.031
their version of a
high-performing business, with
accountability all through the
system

46:07.031 --> 46:09.934
for the teachers and the
principals and using the student
performance as the metric that

46:09.934 --> 46:12.803
everyone had to focus on.

46:12.803 --> 46:15.873
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I mean, it has
been now five years, their
stated time frame. How is

46:15.873 --> 46:18.376
it going in Newark? How
are the kids doing?

46:18.376 --> 46:23.314
DALE RUSSAKOFF: Well, the
charter schools in Newark have
doubled in -- the enrollment

46:23.314 --> 46:27.518
has doubled, and 40 percent of
children in Newark now go to
charter schools, and almost

46:27.518 --> 46:30.655
50 percent of African-American
children go to charter schools.

46:30.655 --> 46:36.294
There has been a big exodus,
particularly in the most
high-poverty districts, which

46:36.294 --> 46:40.464
also are the ones with the most
-- the highest proportion of
African-American kids. Those

46:40.464 --> 46:45.603
skills have performed a lot
better than the district
schools. And so the children in
those

46:45.603 --> 46:49.407
schools are definitely doing
better than they probably would
have done in the district
schools.

46:49.407 --> 46:52.910
As children leave the district
schools, the money follows them.
And there is a huge budget

46:52.910 --> 46:58.182
crisis. There was a $16 million
gap in the school budget. They
have had to close and

46:58.182 --> 47:01.619
consolidate schools. Thousands
of kids have had to change
schools because schools were

47:01.619 --> 47:05.389
closing or consolidating.

47:05.389 --> 47:10.161
Teachers have been laid off.
Support staff, which is a huge
factor in Newark because there

47:10.161 --> 47:15.332
is so much poverty, extreme
poverty, violence, family
dysfunction, the lack of support
staff

47:15.332 --> 47:20.905
is a real problem. So, there's a
lot of factors that are
affecting the district schools,
but

47:20.905 --> 47:25.443
in spite of major effort, they
have not improved. In many
cases, they have gotten worse.

47:25.443 --> 47:30.281
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: One of the
things that you chronicle so
devastatingly in your book is

47:30.281 --> 47:35.386
the failure of the reformers to
bring the community into the
process from the get-go.

47:35.386 --> 47:38.155
Even from the very beginning,
many people learned about this
simply by watching Oprah

47:38.155 --> 47:41.659
on television. How much of that
do you think was a factor in the
results that they have

47:41.659 --> 47:43.494
gotten?

47:43.494 --> 47:48.165
DALE RUSSAKOFF: Well, I don't
know how much of a factor it is
in the student achievement

47:48.165 --> 47:52.269
results, but certainly in the
opposition that the community
rallied against this effort,

47:52.269 --> 47:55.139
that it was the factor.

47:55.139 --> 48:00.044
You know, people have asked me,
was it the unions that brought
upon the reformers all

48:00.044 --> 48:02.480
this opposition? I honestly
don't think the unions were
capable of bringing this much

48:02.480 --> 48:03.214
opposition.

48:03.214 --> 48:05.316
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It was
just there organically?

48:05.316 --> 48:10.321
DALE RUSSAKOFF: Well, I think
the unions helped fan it, but I
think that because this whole

48:10.321 --> 48:14.291
effort was done from outside,
was done to Newark, instead of
with Newark -- that's the

48:14.291 --> 48:17.061
phrase you hear all the time.

48:17.061 --> 48:22.166
The word you hear most often in
Newark in response to this whole
effort is disrespect.

48:22.166 --> 48:28.339
People felt disrespected. And so
I think ordinary parents just
ended up flooding every public

48:28.339 --> 48:33.444
meeting, every school board
meeting, and just trying to stop
this in its tracks.

48:33.444 --> 48:36.180
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Do you think
that would have been different?
Do you think if they

48:36.180 --> 48:40.184
had actively tried to bring the
community along from the
beginning, that it would have

48:40.184 --> 48:42.286
been different?

48:42.286 --> 48:48.225
DALE RUSSAKOFF: Well, you know,
I think bringing the community
along is a complicated idea.

48:48.225 --> 48:53.297
I think, had there been a real
effort to find out from the best
teachers in the district

48:53.297 --> 48:57.868
what do you need to succeed,
what does the school need to
succeed,and has that -- have

48:57.868 --> 49:02.907
those kinds of ideas been at the
heart of trying to improve the
schools, I think then

49:02.907 --> 49:05.676
it would have been viewed as
something that really came more
authentically from the community

49:05.676 --> 49:08.245
and from the people.

49:08.245 --> 49:12.216
It was -- you know, people said
from the beginning, and I think
it was true, that there was a

49:12.216 --> 49:15.319
consensus on the ground that the
Newark schools needed dramatic
change. Nobody thought the

49:15.319 --> 49:18.189
schools -- that the status
quo was acceptable.

49:18.189 --> 49:22.359
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You write that
this was really a collection of
some of the broader

49:22.359 --> 49:27.331
ideas of the reform movement
that have been percolating
across the country.

49:27.331 --> 49:32.069
So does Newark say something
about the broader national
reform movement? What lessons
can

49:32.069 --> 49:37.308
we learn as far as national
educational reform from what has
gone in Newark?

49:37.308 --> 49:44.315
DALE RUSSAKOFF: Well, I think
that the education reform
movement is largely a movement
of,

49:44.315 --> 49:50.154
you know, well-off people,
well-educated people who are
very, very concerned about the
status

49:50.154 --> 49:55.659
of the schools, but -- and the
status of public education
nationally.

49:55.659 --> 50:00.397
I think that there are also
people throughout the poorest
communities that are also very

50:00.397 --> 50:05.069
concerned about education. And I
think the challenge that the
education reform movement

50:05.069 --> 50:10.574
seems concerned with right now
is making sure that all of those
voices in the community,

50:10.574 --> 50:14.511
the affected communities are
part of the answer, as opposed
to just being told what the
answer

50:14.511 --> 50:16.380
is.

50:16.380 --> 50:21.352
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Obviously,
now, five years on, Cory Booker
is in the Senate, Chris Christie

50:21.352 --> 50:25.756
is trying to become president,
but Mark Zuckerberg is still at
this, and -- but doing it in a

50:25.756 --> 50:28.893
slightly different way.

50:28.893 --> 50:32.496
And it seems as if he learned
something from Newark or decided
to change tack. Can you

50:32.496 --> 50:33.430
tell me a little bit about what
he's doing out in California?

50:33.430 --> 50:35.366
DALE RUSSAKOFF: Yes.

50:35.366 --> 50:39.470
Well, he said from the outset
that -- you know, he was 26 when
this started, and he

50:39.470 --> 50:43.407
said he wanted to do something
to help Newark, but he wanted to
become a better philanthropist

50:43.407 --> 50:46.744
in the process, but he was very
open about how little he knew
about philanthropy and

50:46.744 --> 50:49.647
about education.

50:49.647 --> 50:54.551
So, he -- I think he was serious
about that. And the way he's
approaching the latest gift

50:54.551 --> 51:01.292
-- he gave $120 million that's
going to be used in Bay Area
very underserved communities

51:01.292 --> 51:07.331
for school improvement. And
instead of, you know, looking
for a model that can be imposed

51:07.331 --> 51:12.269
on the school districts, he --
and he's had his staff of his
philanthropy spend a lot

51:12.269 --> 51:16.440
of time in the communities to
try to make sure that what the
community wants is what

51:16.440 --> 51:19.810
they're -- that what they're
doing is what the community
wants.

51:19.810 --> 51:23.480
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The book is
called "The Prize: Who's in
Charge of America's Schools?"

51:23.480 --> 51:25.282
Dale Russakoff, thank you
so much for being here.

51:25.282 --> 51:31.088
DALE RUSSAKOFF: Thank you
very much for having me.

